properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall to affect eastern mainland Nova Scotia and Cape Breton tonight and Tuesday. A low pressure system south of Nova Scotia is expected to intensify as it tracks northward toward the province tonight and track just east of Cape Breton Island Tuesday morning. Rain will begin along the Atlantic coast of Nova Scotia early this evening and then spread to the remainder of the province later this evening. Rain will persist over the eastern half of the province on Tuesday. Latest indications are that the heaviest rainfall should occur over eastern Nova Scotia and Cape Breton, where amounts in excess of 40 mm are expected by late Tuesday. Should the system intensify more than currently expected, rainfall warnings may yet be required for these regions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall to affect eastern Prince Edward Island tonight and Tuesday. A low pressure system south of Nova Scotia is expected to intensify as it tracks northward toward the region tonight and track just east of Cape Breton Island Tuesday morning. Rain will likely reach the Island this evening, and will persist over parts of Kings counties on Tuesday. Latest indications are that the heaviest rainfall will occur east of the Island, however easternmost portions of Kings County may receive amounts exceeding 30 mm. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A slow moving low pressure system over central Manitoba continue to bring significant rain to parts of northern Manitoba tonight and Tuesday. Rainfall totals will vary considerably but most areas should expect two day totals of 30 to 50 mm for Monday and Tuesday. Some localities may receive 60 to 80 mm over these two days. Note that while the Churchill Region is included in this warning, current expectations are that the heaviest rain will fall southeast of the town of Churchill. The town of Churchill should expect a total rainfall around 20 to 40 mm for tonight and Tuesday. Rain will begin to ease throughout Northern Manitoba Tuesday night although some rain will continue into Wednesday. Neighbouring regions including Thompson and Island Lakes will see significant rainfall amounts tonight and Tuesday as well. Generally rainfall totals will be less than rainfall warning criteria. ### Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A slow-moving low pressure system over central Manitoba will bring heavy rain to the Norway House region. Rain is will continue today with up to 50 mm expected through the day. Rain will ease off this evening with only a few mm expected overnight, but another bout of rain is expected on Tuesday, with up to 20 mm more possible. Rain will finally ease on Tuesday night. Neighbouring regions including Thompson, Island Lake and Gillam will see significant rainfall amounts today and Tuesday. Generally rainfall totals will be less than rainfall warning criteria in these regions. ### Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Frost Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Frost may damage some crops in frost-prone areas. A ridge of high pressure will build over western sections of the province tonight. Temperatures will approach zero degrees by Tuesday morning with some low lying areas possibly dropping below zero. ### Frost advisories are issued when temperatures are expected to reach the freezing mark during the growing season, leading to potential damage and destruction to plants and crops. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
